Finding Manchester City a New Striker¶

Motivation¶

After the 2020/2021 English Premier League, the top level of English soccer/football, season, champions Manchester City said goodbye to club legend Sergio Aguero, who spent ten years at the club and in that time became their top goalscorer of all time scoring 260 goals for the club. Losing him meant their would be a void in the team and that City would need to dip into the transfer market to find his replacement, however they were unable to do this last season and remain in the hunt for a new striker as the current season comes to a close. Given that he is Manchester City's leading scorer of all time you probably could have guessed his position is a striker, which would be correct. Using popular stat collecting website TransferMarkt I will find which of the worlds best and most promising strikers would be the best fit for Manchester City, taking into account playstyle, build, age, cost, and more. In the table just below you can see the 20 top options from the worlds top five leagues, which include: the English Premier League, the Spanish La Liga, the Italian Serie A, the French Ligue 1, and the German Bundesliga.

Under manager Pep Guardiola, Manchester City have a very particular way of playing that involves keeping the ball for large amounts of time while trying to open up gaps in the opposition defense which means Aguero's replacement needs to be able to keep posession of the ball well. Sometimes opposing teams will employ very defensive tactics to try and not givshots_on_target_pcte any City players space to shoot or find a pass that can lead to a goal so sometimes just putting a ball into the box is what is needed which means someone who is tall and strong or has a good leap would be prefered. Another huge part of Pep's tactics include a high press just after losing the ball or when the oppenent has the ball in their own half so someone who presses and can work hard off the ball is a must. Obviously as a striker your number one job is to score goals so a clinical finisher is a key attribute. Aguero was at City for ten years and became an club icon so ideally a player who has a lot of time ahead of him would be purchased. The last major thing to consider is the cost, especially with the current state of the transfer market being crazily inflated, but money is not too much of an issue for City as they are owned by royalty from the United Arabic Emerates who are super wealthy. That being said they do not just throw cash around, they try to spend money wisely and will not pay crazy amounts just because they have a lot of money. It is also important to consider the team that they currently play for and how that can inflate or deflate certain stats, i.e. Lautaro Martinez plays for Inter Milan who play a very defensive style which means he does not get on the ball a whole lot so he may have less passes than say Kylian Mbappe who plays for Paris Saint-Germain who play a very attacking style and one where he is on the ball very often. With these things considered I will trim the table of its 400 columns to the most important stats and attributes.

Scoring¶

The number one job of any striker is to be scoring goals and that is why I am looking at this metric first. Most of the stats regarding scoring are pretty straight forward. The reason we care about goals per 90 is because that is how long a game lasts and it only takes into account the minutes that are actually played, meaning that if someone is subbed off or on it won't over count their minutes like goals per game would. The other stat that may be unfamiliar is xg which stands for expected goals. This stat takes in numerous factors such as distance, position of defenders, type and speed of pass, type of shot, shot angles, and more. With this you get xg net which shows if the player over or under performed what they were expected to do and would be 0 if they did exactly as expected.

These two plots are not necessarily showing raw ability, but rather efficiency in front of goal which is something Manchester City desperately need as in this season without a recognized striker they have seen numerous chances go to waste. In the half a season Haaland was the most efficient of these players by a landslide. This would be great for City's offensive scheme because at the moment they create chances with ease and the missing piece is a clinical finisher which Haaland clearly is looking at him by these metrics. Being closer to the top right is more valuable in the second plot because even if you do not have an insane xG net as long as you are positive you are scoring at least as much as you should and can still be considered clinical. In addition to that, it is also important to have a high rate of shots on target because even if you do not score you can force a save and the ball could drop to a teammate and give them a high chance to score. Goals per 90 is also something taken into account because if you scored one goal from one shot then you would look great on the efficiency metric but would be lacking overall production.

Based on scoring alone the top 5 options should be: 1) Erling Haaland 2) Kylian Mbappe 3) Robert Lewandowski 4) Ciro Immobile 5) Timo Werner

Possession¶

As I previously stated Pep's style involves keeping the ball for long periods of time to move the defense around, tire them out, and force them to make mistakes which can open up space. Players can adapt to different systems when the move teams but ideally you want them to have some ability to slot in quickly. If you watch City play and watch Pep you can see how upset and angry he gets when one of his players loses the ball especially when it is a result of carelessness. Again most of these stats are fairly clear as to what they are, but sca is something most people have not heard of. SCA is defined as being the two offensive actions that lead to a shot so that can be a dribble, a pass, or being fouled.

The two figures above show important aspects of keeping possession. The first one shows passing and dribbling completion percentages with the passing being the morre important of the two. The reason for this is that Manchester City's forwards all need to be involved the the passing build up to create chances. This might included dropping deep to create some space in behind, finding the right pass on a fast break, passing around the opposition's 18 yard box, and many other situations. Dribbling is a little less important not as a whole, but specifically for strikers. This is because strikers are not going to be on the ball as much as wingers or midfielder and this can be seen as many of the strikers in the table have 65 or less dribbles even attempted. Especially when coming up against a team that plays ultra defensively, which City have to deal with a lot, they will be up against the defense most of the game and a lot of time strikers will be on the end of crosses and will just be shooting. So its a boost if the can dribble well but is one of the attributes that can be seen as less important for strikers. An important thing to not when looking at that graph is that diffence in the range of values, the dribbling percentage has a range of around 50 percent while the passing percentage has a range of about 30 percent. The next plot shows miscontrols and times dispossessed per 90 minutes and unlike the other plots so far it is better to be in the bottom left of the graph rather than the top right. This is fairly intuitive since miscontrolling the ball or having a defender take the ball off of you are very common ways of losing the ball so minimizing this will be important for City. I also included shot creating actions per 90 minutes because the actions that are considered for this stat line up with the stats from the first figure and includes more like being fouled and deflected shots.

Based on these metric the top five options on keeping possession are:

1) Cristiano Ronaldo 2) Rafael Leao 3) Karim Benezma 4) Edinson Cavani 5) Luis Suarez

Out of Possession¶

In order to get into the team in a Pep Guardiola squad you need to work hard when the team does not have the ball including pressing the defenders, cutting off passing lanes, and closing down space. Players also make a big effort to recovering the ball if they misplace a pass or get it stolen from them. Ball recoveries are a combination of many ways to get the ball including intercepting a pass, a successful tackle, a defensive action after a pass, or gathering possession in the defensive third.

The first plot depicts tackles won percentage and the percent of the pressures that leads to the team regaining possession. These two attributes are very important to City's playstyle when they out of the ball as the look to put pressure on the defenders to win back the ball as soon as possible. Putting pressure on the defenders mean they have to try and dribble around or make a pass quicker than they would like, the former plays into the tackles and winning the ball. The latter plays more into the second plot that put pass blocks and interception per 90 minutes against ball recoveries per 90 minutes. Ball recoveries may not be the best metric for strikers since as I said earlier it includes gathering possession in the defensive third so players in defensive styles may have skewed numbers so this stat will be taken with a grain of salt.

With all that in mind the top five for out of possession play are:

1) Antoine Griezmann 2) Victor Osimhen 3) Lautaro Martinez 4) Erling Haaland 5) Luka Jovic

The first plot shows height and aerial duel win percentage. I have stated before that City have to utilze crosses to find ways of scoring so being a big presence in the box is key to doing that. Manchester City also have a many good dribblers which means they win a lot of free kicks and they also have a lot of the ball in the opponents defensive third and have had the most corner kicks in the league with 8.19 per game. Sometimes they have to just clear the ball forward to beat a high press, so being tall and able to win the ball in the air is key in starting a new attack and relieve pressure. The second puts age up against value which focuses more on the business side of the transfer market rather than just looking at statistics from gamees. Both sides of the age spectrum have their values, young can have an extended stay at the club and older can bring experience and a locker room presence. City are in a position where they have a strong locker room with several leaders and with no striker in the squad currently a young star is exactly what the team needs. On the money side of things, City are considerably rich so having the least value is not as crucial as it could be for other teams but they are still looking to make good business and won't spend over the top prices. Note: Robert Lewandoski and Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang have the same age and value.

For this section the top five candidates are:

1) Erling Haaland 2) Rafael Leao 3) Romelu Lukaku 4) Dusan Vlahovic 5) Luka Jovic

Top Option Overall¶

The top option for Manchester City to sign is Erling Haaland as he was in the top five of three of the metrics and was top in two of them, and the most important for his position, scoring. He may not of had the highest marks in keeping possession but as a striker he will not be having to do that as much as other players in his team. He also will have time to adjust after working with one of the best coaches in the world who will demand him to do this to get in the team on a consist basis. This conclusion was made after just looking at stats and sometimes stats do lie and need to be looked at in tandem with the eye test which is just watching the players and seeing things stats don't pick up on like positioning the or runs made that create space for other players.

A couple honorable mentions are Rafael Leao and Luka Jovic if circumstances prevent City from making a move for Haaland.

Predicting Performance¶

Given that City it mostly the same team it was when Aguero left I used his expected goals per game to try and estimate what Haaland's goal per game will be. The reason I used Aguero's numbers is because Haaland will get similar amounts of chances, be in similar positions, and will have the same players feeding him those chances

#Using the data I made a regression line to estimate how many expected goals Haaland will have per game and plotted that
#line along with the actual points from Aguero's time.

years = np.array([2017, 2018, 2019])
newyears = np.array([2020, 2021, 2022])
xgper90 = np.array([.76, .76, .87])
x, y = np.polyfit(years, xgper90, 1)
plt.figure(figsize = (12, 10))
plt.plot(years, xgper90, 'o', color = 'red')
plt.xticks(ticks = [2017, 2018, 2019, 2020, 2021, 2022])
years = np.append(years, newyears)
plt.plot(years, x*years+y)
